      "question": "Can you explain the basic steps for starting an example project if I know the theory but not how to apply it?",
      "answer": "A good way to start an example project when you have theoretical knowledge but don\u2019t know how to apply it is to begin with some background reading and general research on the topic. This helps fill gaps in your knowledge, expand your understanding, and build motivation and confidence. If you\u2019re unsure how to approach the project, ask fellow students, tutors, lecturers, or academic staff for help early on [2].\n\nNext, consider how similar research projects have been done by looking at the theories and methods they used. Be specific about your approach and outline the tasks you will carry out, the methodology (qualitative, quantitative, or mixed-method), and how you will collect data [3].\n\nStarting small is also recommended. For example, you can begin with a weekend side project or pick up a new skill related to your area of interest. Small steps help build momentum and provide valuable lessons even if the project doesn\u2019t fully succeed [6].\n\nIn summary, the basic steps are:\n1. Do background reading and research to build understanding.\n2. Seek advice and support early.\n3. Review similar projects to guide your approach.\n4. Define specific tasks, methodology, and data collection.\n5. Start small with manageable projects to build skills and confidence [2][3][6].",
      "reference": "First, identify the problem. Then decide what data you will use and where it comes from, and check whether it is labelled. After that, split the data into training and testing datasets, and then choose an algorithm to use.",
      "sources": [
