      "question": "What are the five ways of thinking described in the text?",
      "answer": "The five ways of thinking described in the text are:\n\n1. Systems thinking: Looking at the component parts of a system to understand their interactions and relationships as part of a whole.  \n2. Futures thinking: Leveraging foresight methodologies and uncertainty to navigate towards more desirable futures.  \n3. Reframing: Looking at a problem from different perspectives to better define or understand it.  \n4. Sense making: Building a shared understanding of complexity or uncertainty to enable effective decision making.  \n5. Creative problem-solving: Imagining what does not yet exist and thinking beyond conventional solutions, often involving courage to propose uncertain or untested ideas [5][3].",
      "reference": "The five ways are: an inquisitive mind, radical collaboration, bias toward action, mindfulness of process, and re-framing.",
