    {
      "question": "What kinds of things should I avoid doing if I want to stay clear of academic misconduct when creating my assessment?",
      "answer": "To stay clear of academic misconduct when creating your assessment, you should avoid the following:\n\n1. Do not reuse or recycle whole, partially, or reworked assessments for another assessment without getting permission from your tutor, lecturer, or supervisor first [1].\n\n2. Do not work together on assessments that are meant to be completed individually, even if you share ideas and discuss general course content [2].\n\n3. Do not share your assessments or study notes with friends, classmates, or online, even if they just want to 'take a look' [2][3].\n\n4. Do not allow others to change your wording, content, structure, or argument in your assessment; having a friend read your work for typos or minor grammar errors is acceptable, but substantive changes are misconduct [3].\n\n5. Do not use another student\u2019s assessment work when completing an individual task, share your work with others undertaking the same task, communicate with others during take-home exams, or use purchased or online essays or programs as your own [5][6].\n\n6. Always acknowledge sources properly to avoid plagiarism, which includes presenting someone else\u2019s work as your own without appropriate acknowledgement [4].\n\n7. Ensure you complete exams yourself and understand what resources you can access during exams [1].\n\nFollowing these guidelines will help you maintain academic integrity and avoid misconduct [1][2][3][4][5][6].",
      "reference": "Don\u2019t use translation tools to translate your assessment into English, don\u2019t copy someone else\u2019s assessment, and don\u2019t get someone else to write it for you. You should also not buy or use assessments from the internet or file sharing platforms, or use ghost-writing services.",
      "sources": [
        "https://www.uts.edu.au/for-students/current-students/support/academic-support/academic-integrity/create-something-original",
