      "question": "What are some critical questions I can ask when reading academically?",
      "answer": "When reading academically, some critical questions you can ask include:\n\n- Is this information current?  \n- Is there enough academic research backing up the evidence?  \n- Does the writer have a particular agenda that they are pushing?  \n- Is this peer-reviewed data/information?  \n- Is this information reliable?  \n- What else have I read that supports or disagrees with this?  \n- What is the purpose of the text and the main idea or claim being presented?  \n- Do I agree with the argument based on the available evidence?  \n- What is this argument based on?  \n- How does this relate to other concepts I\u2019ve been learning about?  \n- What is my perspective on this issue and why?  \n- What else do I need to find out about this topic to ensure a better understanding or a more balanced perspective?  \n\nThese questions help you evaluate and synthesize information critically as you read academic texts [1][3][4].",
      "reference": "The text says critical reading involves asking questions such as what evidence an argument is based on, how it relates to other concepts you've learned, what your perspective on the issue is and why, and what else you need to find out for a better or more balanced understanding.",
