    {
      "question": "How does UTS prepare students for new film technologies like AI and virtual production?",
      "answer": "UTS prepares students for new film technologies like AI and virtual production by providing opportunities to work with academics and industry professionals to learn how technologies such as AI can support creative work, including generating visuals and shaping sound. Students are encouraged to experiment, test ideas, and build confidence with tools that are already reshaping storytelling. One specific new area of focus is virtual production, which uses LED volumes of screens powered by real-time rendering and game engine technology. UTS also highlights industry examples like Netflix\u2019s use of generative AI for visual effects to show how fast the technology is evolving, especially in post-production [1][2][5].\n\nAdditionally, UTS partners with industry leaders such as ARRI (cinematography), AVID (editing), and the Australian Directors\u2019 Guild (ADG) to support hands-on learning and upskilling through short courses and microcredentials. This approach ensures students gain practical experience and stay current with emerging technologies in the screen industry [2].",
      "reference": "UTS has students work with academics and industry professionals to learn how technologies like AI can support creative work. Students are encouraged to experiment with new tools, and UTS also supports hands-on learning through industry partnerships such as ARRI, AVID and the Australian Directors\u2019 Guild.",
      "sources": [
        "https://www.uts.edu.au/for-students/experience-uts/undergraduate/the-future-of-film-in-australia",
