      "question": "What is U:PASS, and how is it different from tutoring?",
      "answer": "U:PASS is a student learning program at UTS designed to assist students studying subjects that are perceived as difficult or have historically high failure rates, mostly first-year subjects [1]. It is not traditional tutoring but rather group-style study sessions run by high-achieving students who have recently completed the subject [1]. \n\nU:PASS differs from tutoring in that it is peer-led, collaborative, and informal. Sessions are run by experienced students (U:PASS Leaders) who are flexible and responsive to students' abilities and needs, promoting active learning and engagement with the course material in a relaxed setting [2][4]. Unlike formal tutorials or lectures, U:PASS sessions are smaller, less formal, and encourage students to ask questions without embarrassment [2][5]. Attendance is optional, and the program focuses on deeper understanding through group interaction rather than one-on-one instruction typical of tutoring [3].",
      "reference": "U:PASS is a student learning program for subjects that are perceived as difficult or have a high failure rate, mostly first-year subjects. It isn\u2019t tutoring; it offers group-style study sessions run by high-achieving students who recently completed the subject.",
      "sources": [
        "https://www.uts.edu.au/for-students/current-students/support/academic-support/tutoring-and-upass",
        "https://www.uts.edu.au/for-students/current-students/support/upass",
