    {
      "question": "What\u2019s the difference between an appeal and a complaint at UTS?",
      "answer": "An appeal at UTS is a formal opportunity to have an academic or administrative decision reconsidered by the university. Appeals can relate to issues such as fees, student misconduct, academic results, cancellation or suspension of enrolment, and visa status [1]. \n\nA complaint, on the other hand, is about your experience at UTS and can involve dissatisfaction with processes, procedures, course content, interactions with staff, UTS facilities, or programs. Complaints are made when you feel you have been wrongly treated by the university or specific staff members [1][2][5][6].\n\nIn summary, appeals challenge specific decisions made by the university, while complaints address broader issues related to your experience or treatment at UTS. Complaints that are the subject of an appeal are usually dealt with after the appeal process is completed [2].",
      "reference": "An appeal is a formal opportunity to have an academic or administrative decision reconsidered by the university. A complaint is about being wrongly treated by the university or a staff member, or about things related to your experience at UTS.",
      "sources": [
        "https://www.uts.edu.au/for-students/current-students/support/when-things-go-wrong/appeals-and-complaints",
